@KiteWaltzRyder Yeeeep. And I like all the attention that's given to how Souls differs from Bloodborne - the fact I *can* be aggressive and just rush in Bloodborne saved my ass so many times, whereas the same tendencies got me MURDERED in the Souls games. Unsure where Elden Ring is on that!

@KiteWaltzRyder ... Souls games are difficult "for me" is acceptable, though, you know? It may be an ADHD thing but I suck at the sort of pattern recognition necessary for these games to go smoothly. I think certain things are more difficult for some people!

@KiteWaltzRyder Right - the pause function in Elden Ring is a godsend (albeit it's not as simple as just pressing PAUSE), but that's my issue too - I get interrupted a lot when I game, so Souls games are even more difficult than an MMO for me to play regularly. I do think saying that the...

@KiteWaltzRyder ... if I have to grind in a jRPG or MMO, I can watch tv or something while i 'git gud'. I can't really do that with Elden Ring or Bloodborne, so it feels like I'm not making progress even though I am.

@KiteWaltzRyder For me it's a few factors, re: time. Since progress is in fits-and-starts, I don't get the endorphin rush as regularly as say, a regular RPG or a strategy game. I also can't do anything else while playing Soulsborne games, because they require all my attention, whereas even...

@KiteWaltzRyder It's mainly a patience/free time thing. Assuming you don't have an accessibility issue, if you pay enough attention and are willing to spend the time you can get through these games. I almost beat Bloodborne (I stopped at wet nurse for some reason) even though I am TERRIBLE.
